The roots \( z_1 \) and \( z_2 \) are complex conjugates, lying on a circle of radius \( \sqrt{10} \). Their reciprocals \( \frac{1}{z_1} \) and \( \frac{1}{z_2} \) are also complex conjugates, lying on a circle of radius \( \frac{1}{\sqrt{10}} \). The vertices of quadrilateral \( \mathcal{Q} \) are \( z_1 \), \( z_2 \), \( \frac{1}{z_1} \), and \( \frac{1}{z_2} \). Using the parametrization \( z_1 = \sqrt{10} e^{i\theta} \) and \( z_2 = \sqrt{10} e^{-i\theta} \), the reciprocals are \( \frac{1}{z_1} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{10}} e^{-i\theta} \) and \( \frac{1}{z_2} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{10}} e^{i\theta} \). The area of quadrilateral \( \mathcal{Q} \) is calculated using the shoelace formula. The coordinates of the vertices are: 1. \( (\sqrt{10} \cos \theta, \sqrt{10} \sin \theta) \) 2. \( (\sqrt{10} \cos \theta, -\sqrt{10} \sin \theta) \) 3. \( \left( \frac{1}{\sqrt{10}} \cos \theta, -\frac{1}{\sqrt{10}} \sin \theta \right) \) 4. \( \left( \frac{1}{\sqrt{10}} \cos \theta, \frac{1}{\sqrt{10}} \sin \theta \right) \) Using the shoelace formula, the area is found to be proportional to \( \cos \theta \sin \theta \). The maximum value of \( \cos \theta \sin \theta \) occurs at \( \theta = \frac{\pi}{4} \), giving \( \cos \theta \sin \theta = \frac{1}{2} \). At \( \theta = \frac{\pi}{4} \), the value of \( c \) is calculated as \( c = 2 \sqrt{10} \cos \theta = \sqrt{20} \). Therefore, \( c = \sqrt{m} \) implies \( m = 20 \). The value of \( m \) is \(\boxed{20}\).
